      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the ERROR COMM code on my Thermador Pro Grand?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "ERROR COMM indicates a communication fault between the main control board and the broiler module on PRD484NCGU and similar Pro Grand ranges. It's most often triggered by a power event — surge, brownout, breaker trip — or a loose wiring harness at the broiler. Temporary fix is a full power cycle at the breaker for 60 seconds. Permanent fix is inspecting the broiler harness for chafing at the chassis grommet and, if the code repeats after a clean power cycle, replacing the broiler module board. We carry the common Pro Grand control and module boards."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why is my Thermador Star Burner flame orange?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Orange flame on a Star Burner almost always means incomplete combustion from a clogged or misaligned burner head. The small gas port in the burner center feeds the igniter and the flame pattern — grease, cleaning product residue, or spider-web buildup blocks it and the fuel-air mix goes rich. We remove the burner cap and spider, clean the port with a 0.6mm needle, verify the air shutter setting, and re-seat the flame spreader. If orange persists after cleaning, the orifice itself is partially blocked or the regulator pressure is off — both quick fixes at the service call."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you fix the ExtraLow simmer on my Thermador?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. ExtraLow runs on a dedicated XLO solenoid valve and simmer control board — separate from the standard burner valves. When ExtraLow stops holding the 750 BTU simmer point, the failure is usually at the XLO solenoid (sticks partially closed) or the simmer control board (drifts out of calibration). Both are replacement items we stock. Job typically takes 45 minutes once diagnosed."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does Thermador range repair cost?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Diagnostic is $89, waived with repair. Typical Pro Grand jobs: ignition module replacement $320–$450, hot surface igniter $195–$285, main control board (oven) $520–$780, simmer control board (XLO) $340–$490, door latch assembly $210–$310, thermocouple $165–$240, oven thermostat $245–$360. Larger jobs like complete manifold replacement run $750–$1,100. We quote labor and parts before we start."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do you service the Pro Grand Steam 48 with the built-in steam oven?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. The Pro Grand Steam 48 (PRD48JDSGU series) has a dedicated steam generator, water reservoir, descaling cycle, and sensor stack that monitors cavity condition and rack cleanliness. Most 'stuck message' failures — rack clean prompt, water-refill prompt — are sensor contact or descaling-residue issues, not replacement parts. We clear those in one visit. Steam generator replacement is about 3–4 hours and we quote it separately."
        }
