  <!-- ── COMMON PROBLEMS ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Diagnostics and common failures</p>
      <h2>The eight things that break on a Thermador range</h2>
      <p>Eighty percent of the service calls we make on Pro Grand ranges are variations on this list. We carry parts for all eight on the truck.</p>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>1. Star Burner won't light — clicks, no flame</h3>
        <p>The ignition module sends spark to the electrode but the burner stays cold. Two causes, in order of frequency: clogged gas port on the burner head (grease, spilled food, spider web in the feed hole), or a failed hot surface igniter on the affected burner. Clean-out and igniter swap both close the same visit. Parts range: $195–$285 for the igniter, labor typically 45 minutes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>2. Orange flame, flare-up, or yellow tips</h3>
        <p>Incomplete combustion. The small gas port inside the burner is partially blocked, or the air shutter is out of spec, or the regulator is reading the wrong inlet pressure. A Pro Grand running at 14" WC when the manifold wants 10" WC will throw orange flame on the inboard burners first. Diagnostic includes manometer check at the inlet. If the regulator itself is off, we swap it — $240 part, 30 minute job.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>3. ExtraLow simmer won't hold 750 BTU</h3>
        <p>ExtraLow runs on a dedicated XLO solenoid valve and a simmer control board — not the main ignition board. When the simmer drifts up (you set it to low and the pan still boils hard) or won't come on at all, the XLO solenoid is the usual culprit. If the whole ExtraLow system is dead on multiple burners, it's the simmer control board. Both are standard stocked parts for us.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>4. Oven thermostat reads 15–25 °F off</h3>
        <p>Pro Grand ovens drift over time — a temperature sensor that's been cycling between 100°F and 500°F for eight years starts reading low. You'll notice it first on baking: cakes underdone, bread too pale. We verify with a calibrated thermocouple at the rack surface, and if drift exceeds 10°F we replace the temperature sensor. Part is $165, sensor calibration is a 40-minute job. Some owners ask us to "bake it hotter" — we don't do that, the control board fights the offset and things get worse.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>5. Oven door won't close, latch won't engage, self-clean won't start</h3>
        <p>Door latch mechanism. The latch on a Pro Grand is mechanical-electrical — a motor-driven lock that engages before self-clean, and a plunger switch that tells the board the door is closed. Both fail on a common wear curve around year 8–10. Replacement latch assembly runs $210–$310. If the self-clean cycle started and the door locked mid-cycle and won't open, that's the oven lock motor and it's a same-day repair.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>6. Convection fan noise — grinding, buzzing, whine</h3>
        <p>Convection fan motors run for thousands of hours at oven temperature. Bearings dry out, the fan wobbles, and you hear it on every bake cycle. We replace the convection motor with an OEM part ($340–$460 depending on platform) and clean the fan blade. If the grinding has been going on for months, the motor mount and the fan hub are also likely worn — we inspect both on every convection job.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>7. ERROR COMM, F1, E15, or other error codes</h3>
        <p>Pro Grand error codes are usually communication or sensor-related. ERROR COMM is the main control talking to the broiler or simmer board and getting no reply — loose harness or a failed secondary board. F1 is a stuck touchpad. E15 is a moisture or short condition at the control. We carry the service documentation for every error code across all three control generations. Diagnostic pulls the code, isolates to the board, and we quote the fix before ordering parts.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>8. Pro Steam water reservoir and descale cycle</h3>
        <p>The PRD48JDSGU Steam models add a whole parallel water system — reservoir, pump, steam generator, descale sensor. Failures: "refill water" message stuck even with a full tank (sensor contact), descaling cycle won't complete (valve or sensor), steam oven runs cold (generator heating element). Most of these are cleaning and sensor jobs, not parts. The rare parts job — steam generator element — is a 3-hour repair and we quote it before starting.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

