  <!-- ── FAQ ── -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">FAQ</p>
      <h2>Thermador range repair — common questions</h2>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>What's the ERROR COMM code on my Thermador Pro Grand?</summary>
        <p>ERROR COMM means the main control board and the broiler module aren't talking to each other. Most often it's triggered by a power event — surge, brownout, breaker trip. A full breaker-off-60-seconds power cycle clears it temporarily. If it comes back, we inspect the broiler harness for chafing at the chassis grommet, and if needed replace the broiler module board. Common repair, we stock the parts.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>Why is my Star Burner flame orange?</summary>
        <p>Incomplete combustion. The small gas port in the burner head is partially blocked — usually grease or cleaning product residue in the igniter channel. The fuel-air mix goes rich, you get orange flame and sooting. We remove the burner cap and spider, clear the port with a 0.6mm needle, verify the air shutter setting, and re-seat the flame spreader. If orange persists after a full cleanup, the orifice or the regulator pressure is off — also quick fixes.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>Can you fix the ExtraLow simmer?</summary>
        <p>Yes. ExtraLow runs on a dedicated XLO solenoid valve and a simmer control board, independent of the main burner valves. When the simmer drifts up or won't hold 750 BTU, it's usually the XLO solenoid (sticking partially closed) or the simmer board (calibration drift). Both are stocked parts — 45-minute job in most cases.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>How much does a typical Thermador range repair cost?</summary>
        <p>Diagnostic is $89, waived with repair. Common jobs fall in these ranges: ignition module $320–$450, hot surface igniter $195–$285, main oven control board $520–$780, simmer control board $340–$490, door latch $210–$310. Labor and parts quoted before work starts. See the pricing table on this page for the full list.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>Do you service the Pro Grand Steam 48?</summary>
        <p>Yes. The Pro Grand Steam 48 (PRD48JDSGU series) has its own water reservoir, pump, steam generator, and descaling sensor stack. Most Steam failures are sensor or descaling-residue issues — cleared in one visit. Steam generator element replacement is a 3–4 hour job and we quote it separately before starting.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>I spilled water into the control area of my PRD486 — now what?</summary>
        <p>Turn off the gas at the shutoff and power at the breaker immediately. Don't run the range until we've pulled the top and dried the electronics. Depending on what shorted, common damage is ignitor board ($285), oven lock motor ($225), simmer board ($420) — sometimes all three. Moisture damage is covered under most homeowner insurance if the spill was accidental.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>How fast can you come out?</summary>
        <p>Same-day on calls before 1 PM weekday inside regular coverage. Malibu, Hidden Hills, and Pacific Palisades usually get next-morning priority. For a dead Pro Grand with a dinner party tonight, call and say so — we rearrange routing for emergencies.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq">
        <summary>Are you Thermador Factory-Certified?</summary>
        <p>No — we're factory-trained but independent. If your range is inside the 2-year major-parts warranty, call Thermador at 1-800-735-4328 first — they'll dispatch a Factory-Certified contractor at no parts cost. After the warranty window, we're usually the better call: faster, lower labor rate, same technical grade. Same BSH platform training.</p>
      </details>
